🚀 Example Workflow: Canary Deploy with HyperSwarm
This example shows how HyperSwarm handles a real-world intent: spinning up a canary deploy and validating error rate against SLOs.

1. User Intent
In the Intent Box, the user types:

Spin up a canary deploy and validate error rate < 0.1%

and hits Execute. The frontend sends this to the orchestrator, which begins processing.

2. System Boot & Connection
When the Control Center starts up and connects, the Activity Log shows:

text
[11:59:30 PM] SYSTEM: HyperSwarm Control Center initialized
[11:59:30 PM] SYSTEM: ✅ Connected to HyperSwarm Network
[11:59:30 PM] SYSTEM: Initiating neural link.
This confirms:

The UI is live and healthy.

The backend and agents are reachable.

The user can safely start sending intents.

3. Intent → Task → Plan
After the user submits the canary deploy intent, the agents create and accept a concrete execution plan:

text
[12:12:14 AM] CONDUCTOR: Processing intent: "Spin up a canary deploy and validate error rate < ..."
[12:12:15 AM] ORCHESTRATOR: 🆕 Task Created: task_20260223_001215
[12:12:16 AM] ORCHESTRATOR: ✅ Plan accepted. ID: task_20260223_001215
What’s happening here:

CONDUCTOR parses the natural language intent and turns it into a structured workflow (e.g., steps to create canary, route traffic, collect metrics).

ORCHESTRATOR persists this as a new task (task_20260223_001215).

The plan is validated and accepted, meaning all required agents and tools are available and the cost/safety constraints are satisfied.

At this point, the Visual Cortex graph will highlight the agents involved in the workflow, and the Cost Tracker will begin to reflect any spend associated with the task.

4. Why This Matters
This sequence illustrates the core HyperSwarm loop:

You think in intents.

CONDUCTOR thinks in workflows.

ORCHESTRATOR thinks in tasks and guarantees.

The Activity Log gives you a clear, timestamped narrative from “Control Center initialized” to “Plan accepted”, and the stable task_20260223_001215 id lets you visually and mentally track your workflow even while background load is running.